1) Spring @Transactional Self-Invocation Problem
Description: A service has 2 methods with @Transactional on it. methodA() and methodB().
methodA() call methodB() in it.
@Service
public class MyService {

    @Transactional  // Transaction T1 starts via proxy
    public void methodA() {
        // ... some logic
        this.methodB(); // ← PROBLEM: 'this' = raw object, not proxy
                        // methodB runs in T1's context, NOT a new transaction
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void methodB() {
        // EXPECTS: Suspend T1, start new T2
        // REALITY: Still running in T1 — REQUIRES_NEW is ignored
    }
}
-------------
RC & Solution
-------------
RC: Spring @Transactional works via AOP proxies (JDK Dynamic Proxy or CGLIB).
The proxy wraps the bean and intercepts calls.
But self-invocation (this.methodB()) bypasses the proxy entirely — PROPAGATION_REQUIRES_NEW on methodB() never triggers a new transaction.

Solution: Fix-1, Fix-2 and Fix-3

✅ Fix 1: Self-Injection (Simplest — Spring 4.3+): Inject the bean itself so the call goes through the proxy.
@Service
public class MyService {

    @Autowired
    private MyService self; // Spring injects the proxy

    @Transactional
    public void methodA() {
        self.methodB(); // ← Goes through proxy, REQUIRES_NEW honored
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void methodB() {
        // T1 suspended, new T2 starts — correct behavior
    }
}


✅ Fix 2: Extract to a Separate Bean (Recommended for Clean Architecture)
java
@Service
public class MyServiceA {

    @Autowired
    private MyServiceB myServiceB;

    @Transactional
    public void methodA() {
        myServiceB.methodB(); // ← External call through proxy — correct
    }
}

@Service
public class MyServiceB {

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void methodB() {
        // Properly runs in a new independent transaction
    }
}

This is the cleanest and most production-preferred approach — better separation of concerns, no circular dependencies.

✅ Fix 3: Fetch Proxy via AopContext (When refactoring isn't feasible)
java
@Service
public class MyService {

    @Transactional
    public void methodA() {
        ((MyService) AopContext.currentProxy()).methodB(); // Explicit proxy call
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void methodB() { }
}
Requires @EnableAspectJAutoProxy(exposeProxy = true)

